list.title: You're Too Gullible About Science
list.description:
Nice try! You didn't know many of the answers to the questions, yet you made it to the end of the quiz, so now you know more about what's true in science (and what's not).

Think critically when presented with science "facts". It's okay to be skeptical. You can apply the scientific method to help identify what is true.

From here, you can test the critical thinking ability of others, by seeing whether they can understand simple science magic tricks.

list.text: Some spiders have 6 legs rather than 8.

reveal.text: All spiders have 8 legs, although sometimes they may appear to have more because of the length of specialized appendages called chelicerae. Insects, on the other hand, have 6 legs.

image.alt: Close up of Tube web spider, Segestria florentina, on white background

list.text: Days are getting longer over time.

reveal.text: Days are gradually getting longer. The rotation of the Earth is slowing slightly over time. The increase is about 1.4 milliseconds every hundred years.

image.alt: Digital planet

list.text: The Great Wall of China is visible from space.

image.alt: Great Wall

reveal.text: The Great Wall of China is not visible from space. The Apollo astronauts could not see it from the Moon. International Space Station Commander Leroy Chiao did take a photograph from the ISS in which you can just barely make out the Wall, but that's low Earth orbit and not actually space. It might be more accurate to say that the Great Wall is not visible from space without magnification.

image.alt: Planet Earth from Space

list.text: Most people use only 10% of their brains.

image.alt: Human brain

reveal.text: You use all of your brain, just not all at once. This widely held science myth was disproved once scientists started imaging brain activity.

list.text: Dry ice melts into liquid carbon dioxide as it warms in a room.

image.alt: Dry Ice

reveal.text: At ordinary temperature and pressure, dry ice sublimates directly into carbon dioxide gas, without a liquid phase. Liquid carbon dioxide can exist, but only if the pressure is controlled.

image.caption: The dry ice in this photo is sublimating in blue-colored water.
image.alt: The dry ice in this photo is sublimating in blue-colored water.

list.text: If you swallow gum, it stays in your stomach/intestines for 7 years.

image.alt: Twins eating chewing gum

reveal.text: Most modern chewing gum is made from indigestible polymers. If you swallow it, it passes through your digestive system unchanged. While rare, it's possible for gum or other undigestable matter to get stuck in the intestines and form a calcified body called a bezoar. Bezoars form in ruminants much more often than in humans.

list.text: The sky can appear green during some thunderstorms.

image.alt: Kansas green storm

reveal.text: Green clouds are due to the scattering of light by water. Green seems most common when ice or hail is present in cumulus clouds. It's not common, but it does occur (and usually signifies a severe storm).

image.alt: Supercell storm

list.text: A cockroach can live up to a couple of weeks without a head.

image.alt: Blaberus giganteus (giant cockroach)

reveal.text: Yes, it's true. Cockroaches can live for weeks without their heads. Another interesting fact is that the insects can go for 6 weeks without eating, and then, they can eat just about anything. Soap, hair, leather... you name it.

image.alt: Dead cockroach

list.text: Urinating on a jellyfish sting is an effective remedy.

image.owner: Feria Hikmet Noraddin / EyeEm / Getty Images
image.alt: Jellyfish Swimming In Sea

reveal.text: Peeing on a jellyfish sting will not help and may even make the situation worse, if the sting is from a Man o' War. Heat, as from hot sand, or an acid or base (vinegar or baking soda) can inactivate the toxic protein.

image.alt: Sunset through the smog over Shanghai China

reveal.text: Particles in smog scatter light, which can make sunrises and sunsets appear more red.

image.caption: Red Sunset
image.alt: Red Sunset
